#compdef moq
# Documentation: source-direct extraction from upstream
# matryer/moq main.go (Go-based CLI using **Go stdlib
# `flag` package** — same library family as R264 ctop,
# but uses the **`flag.StringVar` / `flag.BoolVar`
# write-to-pointer variants** instead of ctop's
# pointer-returning forms):
#   main.go lines 18-27 (userFlags struct with 7 fields
#     + args slice)
#   main.go lines 29-63 (main fn: 8 flag declarations,
#     custom flag.Usage, positional handling via
#     flag.Args())
#   main.go lines 31-41 (flag.StringVar + flag.BoolVar
#     7 declarations + 1 pointer-returning flag.Bool —
#     MIXED patterns in same CLI)
#   main.go lines 43-48 (custom flag.Usage override:
#     usage line + flag.PrintDefaults() + custom
#     interface-alias example lines)
#   main.go line 51 (positional args extracted via
#     `flag.Args()` after flag.Parse())
#   main.go lines 66-67 (positional minimum: at least 2
#     args required — source-dir + interface)
# Reference accessed: 2026-05-30 via gh api.
#
# moq is the **Go interface mock generator** from
# matryer — generates Go mock implementations from
# interface definitions for use in testing.  Pivots from
# container TUI (R264 ctop) into the **Go testing
# tooling cluster**.  Sister to mockgen (in corpus),
# testify (in corpus).  Continues the Go-stdlib-flag
# documentation series (R264 ctop established the
# library taxonomy; R265 moq documents a different
# variant within the same library).
#
# Critical extraction note: moq uses **`flag.StringVar`
# / `flag.BoolVar` write-to-pointer variants** at
# main.go:31, 32, 33, 34, 37, 39, 40 — distinct from
# R264 ctop's pointer-RETURNING `flag.String("name",
# "default", "help") *string`.  StringVar signature:
# `flag.StringVar(p *string, name, defaultValue, help
# string)`.  Writes to user-provided `&var` directly so
# the calling code accesses `flags.outFile` instead of
# `*outFileFlag`.  Documents the **2 stdlib-flag access
# patterns**: (a) pointer-returning form (R264 ctop),
# (b) write-to-pointer form via StringVar/BoolVar (R265
# moq).  The Var-form is more idiomatic when collecting
# flags into a struct (like moq's `userFlags`); the
# pointer-returning form is more idiomatic when flags
# are local variables.  Documents the **stdlib-flag
# struct-collection pattern** for grouped flag handling.
#
# Critical extraction note: moq uses **MIXED PATTERNS
# in the same CLI** at main.go:36 — `printVersion :=
# flag.Bool("version", false, "show the version for
# moq")` is the pointer-returning form, while the OTHER
# 7 flags use the StringVar/BoolVar write-to-pointer
# form.  Documents the **mixed-stdlib-flag-patterns
# reality** — moq's authors used the pointer-returning
# form for `--version` (a local-only flag that doesn't
# need to flow into the `userFlags` struct) but the
# struct-write form for everything that needs to flow
# into the run-fn.  Practical hybrid usage.
#
# Critical extraction note: moq uses **custom
# `flag.Usage` function** at main.go:43-48 — overrides
# the default help format with: (a) usage line printed
# first, (b) `flag.PrintDefaults()` for the flag list,
# (c) extra lines explaining the `interface:alias`
# syntax with an example.  Documents the **custom
# flag.Usage override pattern** — Go's stdlib flag
# package allows replacing the default help generator
# by assigning to `flag.Usage`.  Distinct from R264
# ctop's separate `printHelp` fn (called manually from
# `*helpFlag` branch).  moq's approach is more idiomatic:
# `flag.Usage` is automatically called when parsing
# fails or `-h` is passed.  Corpus's **first documented
# `flag.Usage` override**.
#
# Critical extraction note: moq uses **positional args
# via `flag.Args()`** at main.go:51 — after
# `flag.Parse()`, `flag.Args()` returns the remaining
# (non-flag) arguments as `[]string`.  moq expects at
# least 2 positionals: `source-dir` + at least 1
# interface name (with optional `:alias` suffix).  The
# minimum check at line 66 (`if len(flags.args) < 2 {
# return errors.New("not enough arguments") }`) is
# manual.  Documents the **stdlib-flag positional
# handling** — distinct from R263 lazygit's flaggy
# `AddPositionalValue` with required-flag and R249
# cairo-profiler's clap derive positional with
# `num_args = 1..`.  Stdlib flag has NO positional
# declaration syntax; positionals are just "everything
# after the parsed flags".
#
# Critical extraction note: moq supports
# **`interface:alias` syntax for naming the generated
# mock** — e.g. `moq -pkg different . MyInterface:MyMock`
# generates a mock for `MyInterface` named `MyMock`
# instead of the default `MyInterfaceMock`.  The
# alias-syntax parsing is in pkg/moq (not main.go).
# Documents the **colon-separated positional alias
# pattern** in CLI design — a single positional with
# embedded structure (`name:alias`) parsed by the
# downstream library.  Distinct from R248 cairo-
# coverage's `value_parser = fn` (which validates a
# whole positional) — moq's colon-form is a STRUCTURAL
# parse (split + assign roles).

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line

# Formatter values from --fmt help text at main.go:33:
# `gofmt, goimports or noop`.
local -a formatters=(
  'gofmt:standard go fmt (default)'
  'goimports:goimports (organize imports + format)'
  'noop:no formatting (raw output)'
)

# Go stdlib flag treats `-X` and `--X` as the same flag
# (every flag accepts both forms).
_arguments -s -S \
  '(-h -help --h --help)'{-h,-help,--h,--help}'[show help (calls custom flag.Usage)]' \
  '(-version --version)'{-version,--version}'[show the version for moq]' \
  '(-out --out)'{-out+,--out=}'[output file (default: stdout)]:file:_files -g "*.go"' \
  '(-pkg --pkg)'{-pkg+,--pkg=}'[package name (default: infer from source-dir)]:package:' \
  '(-fmt --fmt)'{-fmt+,--fmt=}'[Go pretty-printer]:formatter:(($formatters))' \
  '(-stub --stub)'{-stub,--stub}'[return zero values when no mock impl provided (do not panic)]' \
  '(-skip-ensure --skip-ensure)'{-skip-ensure,--skip-ensure}'[suppress mock impl check (avoids import cycles when mocks generated outside tested package)]' \
  '(-rm --rm)'{-rm,--rm}'[remove output file first if it exists]' \
  '(-with-resets --with-resets)'{-with-resets,--with-resets}'[generate functions to facilitate resetting mock call records]' \
  '1:source-dir:_files -/' \
  '*:interface[:alias] (e.g. MyInterface or MyInterface:MyMock):'
